When correctly placed, the 2nd line from the bottom passes through the loop of the G and last line barely touches the bottom of the loop. Makes it a bit difficult to understand the notes. In fact, I find it easier to hide the clef symbol with a thumb and then practice. I wish the dev would fix the app as otherwise it's excellent.

This app has some good qualities for novices but for intermediate level it fails in two areas: even though the staff spans multiple octaves in advanced mode, the keyboard only shows one octave, which means you're actually playing the wrong notes on the keyboard relative to what's notated. Secondly there is no grand staff, you can only choose between treble or bass, but not both at once.

I have spent a significant amount of energy exploring music theory apps in both the Google Play and the iTunes store. I believe I have used more than 75% of them. Out of all of the music theory apps I have used, I believe this is the best at what it does, which is note identification training.  The unfortunate reality is that the Play Store's selection of music theory apps is severely lacking compared to iTunes. There are no good "all purpose" apps like Musicopoulos, Music Theory Pro, or iHarmony. However, when it comes to straight up sheet music note identification, this is the best app around. The scoring and difficulty scaling are second to none. The in app piano is the best I've encountered (a week of playing and the app has yet to mis-identify a note I was trying to hit). The UI is sleek and aesthetically pleasing. The only fault in this otherwise perfect app is the fact that their is no timer mode. However, this omission is not enough to dethrone this app from its rightful position as king of note identification.

I'm looking for good clef-reading programs for my students - so far I've tried nine different android apps and this one is one of my favorites.   It's a nice design - notes travel from right to left on your screen and you've got to play them on a piano keyboard before they "crash" into the end.  However, my one complaint is that it should offer a chance to queue up a difficult game.  As far as I can tell the game always starts on "wave 1" and you have to play through very boring levels before it gets interesting.  One way to create more difficulty would be to start waves with several notes already on screen so you've got to scramble to catch up.    Also, I would like it to have an input option with abstract buttons that say "A" "B" "C" etc rather than a piano keyboard - to make it more universal and not necessarily piano-centric.  But, like I said, in a sea of pretty terrible note-reading apps this one stands out as solid.

I am 45 years old and just started piano lessons with no previous music experience.  I found sight reading to be intimidating, and was looking for some study aids outside of lesson. I tried  few other apps, but Note Trainer is the best so far.  I can do treble or bass, with or without sharps and flats. There is a practice mode that combines notes recognition with finding the key on the piano, which helps prepare you for reading and playing at the same time. There is also a play mode which streams notes across the board in progressively faster waves and it keeps track of your scoring. I installed today and spent about 1 hour on it and can already see an improvement in my recognition and scores. My daughter who has been playing piano for 5 years even enjoyed testing her ability in the play mode. Haven't encountered any bugs or crashes.  Thanks for this most useful app!!
